    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "oh ok so it's more about the pH level than the acid itself. that makes sense. but like, how does the body actually handle it in the moment? like if i'm right in the middle of a set and it starts burning, what's the step by step on how those molecules are getting produced and why does it feel so disruptive to the muscles?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "During intense exercise, your muscles rely on anaerobic glycolysis to generate energy without enough oxygen, which causes lactate to build up along with significant amounts of hydrogen ions. These hydrogen ions disrupt the chemical signaling between muscles and nerve cells, messing up calcium release and making your fibers difficult to contract, which creates the burning sensation. Your body tries to buffer this increase in acidity by using substances like bicarbonate and phosphate (and even proteins like carnosine) to neutralize the hydrogen ions, but the sheer volume produced faster than they can be neutralized causes the overload and pain. Once the intensity drops and oxygen becomes available, aerobic metabolism helps clear the lactate efficiently, and the buffering systems restore the normal pH so your muscles can work again.",
      "source": "target",
