    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Imagine the muscle fibers as tiny motors where a signal tells them to contract; the burning sensation occurs because too many hydrogen ions infiltrate these motors and interfere with the electrical signals that trigger the movement, effectively short-circuiting the mechanism. This isn't about physical friction from chemical gunk, but rather a disruption of the chemistry that controls when muscles squeeze, making it hard to recruit enough fibers for a strong contraction. Once you push back harder or slow down, your body uses oxygen-based processes to reverse this chemistry quickly, allowing the \"short circuits\" to clear and your original motor function to return.",
      "source": "target",
